04065nam a22005655i 9780774837453DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748374537 a10.59962/97807748374532doi  a(DE-B1597)662015  a(OCoLC)1142184506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE98.W8bG73 2020 7aSOC0620002bisacsh04a305.897 00822231 aGranzow, Kara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInvested Indifference :bHow Violence Persists in Settler Colonial Society /cKara Granzow. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (284 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tA History of the Present: Methodology -- t“It in no way makes you safer” Contemporary Policing and Remaking the City -- t“All they could to help” Imaging, Diagnosing, and Transforming Indian Tuberculosis and the City -- t“All traces of his footsteps are fast being obliterated” Fictioning and Controlling Land and Life -- t“Just bury them and be done with it” Managing Affect and Producing the Past -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2004, Amnesty International characterized Canadian society as “indifferent” to high rates of violence against Indigenous women and girls. When the Canadian government took another twelve years to launch a national inquiry, that indictment seemed true. Invested Indifference offers a divergent perspective by examining practices during three different periods in the place we now call Edmonton, juxtaposing early settler texts, documents concerning the former Charles Camsell Indian Hospital, and contemporary online police materials. Kara Granzow reaches a startling conclusion: that what we see as societal indifference doesn’t come from an absence of feeling but from a deep-rooted and affective investment in framing specific lives as disposable. Granzow demonstrates that through mechanisms such as the law, medicine, and control of land and space, violence against Indigenous peoples has become symbolically and politically ensconced in the social construction of Canadian nationhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous womenxViolence againstzAlbertazEdmonton. 0aIndigenous womenzAlbertazEdmontonxSocial conditions. 0aViolencezAlbertazEdmonton. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483745340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774837453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774837453/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles